prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
This portion of the Technical Justification is for the sample of 39 objects with stellar masses lower than 0.3 solar masses and greater than 0.05 solar masses (SpTy between M7 and M3, 2,800K<T<3,400K, herefater Cool Sample). This SB was approved in Cycle2 (our proposal 2013.1.00437.S received a B grade) but not executed before the ALMA Cycle3 deadline.
Our primary goals require photometric measurements at 850 micron but no high spatial resolution to resolve the disks. The peak continuum flux densities we report in the OT are those computed using a Mdisk and Mstar relation consistent with that inferred from the Hot Sample and randomizing the fluxes to account for the observed spread.
Choice of observing band: We have chosen Band7 over Band6(1.3mm) because it is the most sensitive band when taking into account the sensitivity of the instrument and the spectral index of the dust opacity.
Sensitivity: For the Cool Sample we require a 1 sigma sensitivity on the aggregated continuum bandwidth of 0.2 mJy. This sensitivity is 15 times better than current surveys at 850 micron and is set to detect all but a few disks (depending on the spread in disk masses) for a linear Mdisk-Mstar relation (alpha=1). The Monte Carlo simulations we carried out in preparation of our Cycle2 proposal showed that we will be able to establish the Mdisk-Mstar relation even for alpha as large as 2 with this sensitivity. This science goal requires a total time (including overheads) of ~2.5 hours.

We will use 3 basebands to detect the 850 micron continuum emission from protoplanetary disks. The 4th baseband is devoted to the serendipitous detection of the CO(3-2) line. For this band we have chosen a resolution of 0.2km/s, enough to spectrally resolve even the narrowest gas lines around the lowest mass objects in our sample (the Keplerain width for gas at 50AU around a 0.05 solar mass star is 1km/s).

Our science goals do not require to spatially resolve protoplanetary disks, hence we have chosen a resolution of 1 arcsec, compact ALMA configuration. However, slightly better resolutions, down to 0.4arcsec, are also fine (configurations C36-1, C36-2, and C36-3).

These are the 14 fields centered on sources with stellar masses >= 0.3 solar masses which remain undetected at the 3sigma sensitivity of 1.2X3 = 3.6mJy/beam of our Cycle2 observations.
Most of these sources are M0-M3 stars, their non detection suggests that the Mdisk-Mstar relation is steeper than linear but sensitive observations of the low-mass M stars are needed to make a firm statement.
We propose to re-observe these fields with the same setup and sensitivity as that of the Cool Sample, a sensitivity on the 850micron continuum that is 6 times better than that achieved in Cycle2.

We will use 3 basebands to detect the 850 micron continuum emission from protoplanetary disks. The 4th baseband is devoted to the serendipitous detection of the CO(3-2) gas line. For this band we have chosen a 0.2km/s resolution which is adequate to spectrally resolve and model even the narrowest gas lines around the lowest mass objects in our sample (the Keplerian width for gas at 50AU around a 0.05 solar mass star is 1km/s).

Our science goals do not require to spatially resolve protoplanetary disks, hence we have chosen a resolution of 1 arcsec, compact ALMA configuration. However, slightly better resolutions, down to 0.4arcsec, are also fine (configurations C36-1, C36-2, C36-3).

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: A fundamental parameter of every planet formation is the disk mass. Indeed, the occurrence rate of exoplanets shows trends that are likely the result of stellar mass-dependent disk masses. We propose to measure the masses of all Chameleon I disks around objects from ~2 to 0.05 solar masses in order to: 1) establish how the disk mass scales with the mass of the central star and 2) constrain average disk masses and their spread over a range of 40 in stellar mass. We were awarded ALMA Cycle 2 time for this survey but only one of our two SBs, the one comprising 54 stars with masses >= 0.3 solar masses, has been executed. This limited dataset hints that the disk mass-stellar mass relation is steeper than linear but the SB with the 39 lower-mass objects is necessary to reach our science goals. Here, we request observation of that SB, as well as re-observation of 14 M-K stars, 7 of which are ~0.3 solar mass stars, at the same sensitivity as for the lower-mass objects. Our survey, in combination with ancillary data we are assembling, will also test disk dispersal theories and provide an ALMA legacy for follow-up studies of disks around young stars.
